    <item>
      <title>Re: Is EQ good?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=TNZ&amp;message.id=228103#M228103</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Does a one legged duck swim in circles?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Is a frog's a*s watertight? &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Does a teddy bear have cotton balls? &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Really, it's all subjective but here's my experience.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;EQ is the granddaddy of graphical MMO's.  You are here so you at least generally know how the game works.  We have specific Classes and Races, chosen at character creation, that we advance in levels and capabilities as we adventure through Norrath.  We can learn many tradeskills that we can use to turn raw materials we find on our adventures into useful items such as Armor, Weapons and all sorts of gadgets.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In EQ2, you have a radically changed Norrath where the Good side lives in Qeynos and the Evil side lives in Freeport - but there is no ongoing battle between these factions - it feels like a storyline that was just left hanging.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In EQ2, once you start a fight with a creature in the world, the encounter becomes locked to you.  No one can kill-steal from you, but they also can not help you whatsoever.   You can't heal them, buff them, slow the mob for them - anything.  If the mob is &amp;quot;tied&amp;quot; to other mobs, forming a &amp;quot;group&amp;quot;, you can not separate them - if you pull one, you pull them all.  No tactics - just drag and kill.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;When you start a new toon in EQ2, you choose a Race and one of 4 &amp;quot;general&amp;quot; Classes - Fighter, Mage, Priest, Scout.  Later on as you hit the milepost levels (10 &amp;amp; 20 iirc), you further refine your Class and choose a sub-class, i.e., Fighters break up into Warriors, Paladins, Shadowknights, Priests become Clerics, Druids, Shamans....Mages become Wizards, Enchanters, Magicians...Scouts break up into Rogues, Rangers and Bards, etc.  This is a simplified breakdown and from memory so is not completely accurate or complete but illustrates their idea.  My problem with this system was that my preferred Class, Ranger, was developed based on the Rogue - all about stealth, sneaking up behind mobs and backstabbing....as a foundation for Rangers and Bards?  Rangers are about archery and Bards are about music.  What do either have to do with Stealth and Backstabbing? Totally wacked idea imho.  Yeah, my Ranger in EQ has sneak and hide but such a low skill cap in both that they are useless....and no backstab, pick locks or pick pockets - so why did the EQ2 peeps think a Ranger has anything to do with being a thief?.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In EQ2, buffs are all group-based.  It was kind of handy not having to re-cast buffs when new members joined the group as their buffs were automatically shared with you and vice-versa - but the drawbacks became readily apparent.  If you get too far away from your group, your buffs suddenly disappear.  If you are in a group with another member of the same class, and they are higher level than you, then their buff overwrites your own, and once you get out of &amp;quot;range&amp;quot; you end up losing your own buff and have to re-cast it on yourself - which then gets overwritten again once you get back in &amp;quot;range&amp;quot; of the group.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Tradeskills in EQ2 are equally gimped.  To begin with, you can only truly learn one skill.  That skill will then be dependent on other trades to supply your sub-combines.  But it doesn't work that way.  Where the designers obviously intended for a market of goods to form where you go shopping for your sub-components, people ended up creating alts to feed their mains with the subs.  The market never really materialized beyond people selling raw materials.  To add insult to injury, what started out as a cool side-game inside the main game, rapidly became an exercise in extreme patience.  Where it may take you a loooong time to raise your smithing in EQ to a high level, it will take you 10 times longer in EQ2.  Not because of the rate of skillups, but because of the excruciatingly slow mechanism they created for performing combines.  What takes a coupls of seconds in EQ takes a couple of MINUTES in EQ2.  For ONE combine!  As a simple example, I can crank out 80 combines of Blessed Champion Arrows in about 30 minutes in EQ - that includes making the arrowheads, shafts and fletchings.  In EQ2 it took me about 5 HOURS to complete a comparable run of arrows there.  NEVER AGAIN!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;All things considered, EQ2 is NOTHING like EQ and in no way whatsoever deserves the EverQuest name.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Ok, on to WoW.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;I found WoW to be a LOT of fun.  It is similar to EQ in that you choose a Race and Class at character creation and that is what that character will be forever.  Zones in WoW are not separated like they are in EQ and EQ2 - the only &amp;quot;zoning&amp;quot; occurs when moving between the 2 continents in Azeroth, or when entering or leaving an instanced zone.  Buffs work like they do in EQ - you can cast buffs and heals on toons outside your group.  You can actually help people in trouble!  What a concept!  (Not that it actually happens all that often, but at least it IS possible).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Most of your experience in WoW is generated from doing quests.  You get experience from each mob you kill as you do in EQ and EQ2, and Blizzard doesn't hide the actual numbers from you.  You know that it will take you X experience points to reach the next level, and that you got Y experience from killing that rat, or completing whatever quest.  The quests are fun, you get large chunks of XP on completion, and many of them offer items such as weapons and armor in addition to the XP.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The environment in WoW really impressed me.  While the graphics are not as &amp;quot;bleeding edge&amp;quot; as EQ2's are, they are extremely well done and create so much more Atmosphere than I ever felt in EQ2.  Transitioning from a desert area to a mountain zone, you really &amp;quot;feel&amp;quot; the mood change.  Bright, bold, beautiful colors make for a much more inviting world than the highly-detailed, washed out looking pastel world of EQ2.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Tradeskills in WoW are very simple in comparison to EQ or EQ2.  While the interface is more like EQ in that you don't have some tedious little time-consuming &amp;quot;game&amp;quot; to perform your combines, you are limited in that you can only choose 1 &amp;quot;profession&amp;quot;.  All of the professions in WoW offer something to generate income, but not much.  Most of the player-made items in the game are either usable only by the profession that created it, or are gimped in comparison to the items found adventuring.  One nice feature of the WoW TS interface is the All button.  It will repeatedly preform a selected combine for all of the materials you have in inventory - or until you stop it.  Very handy single-click to crank out a pile of bandages, for example.  Some folks consider this just a bit TOO easy.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Of all these games though, WoW does Fishing the best.   EQ is simply throw your line in some water, wait a minute, spill your beer, and wind up with either a fish, piece of junk, or nothing on your hook.  In EQ2, its a weird system of seeing a &amp;quot;school&amp;quot; of fish in some water and using your &amp;quot;grabbing hand&amp;quot; icon to &amp;quot;fish&amp;quot;.  Oddness abounds there.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In WoW, you throw your line in some water and you see your bobber floating out there in the water in front of you.  You have to sit there and watch that thing - when you see it dip under the water (indicating a fish biting) you have to click it within a couple of seconds to &amp;quot;hook&amp;quot; the fish.  Very interactive and very difficult to &amp;quot;bot&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The drawback to WoW to me, is that the end-game is nothing but Raiding, Faction Grinding, or PvP.  They even go so far as to lock your experience bar when you ding 60, so that you can't even fill it up - obviously they don't want anyone insta-dinging when they inevitably raise the level cap.  So, from that point on, every mob you kill, every quest you complete - you get awarded the XP but it just goes up in smoke.  VERY frustrating.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Blizzard could very easily have done somthing for the end game like what Verant did for EQ - Alternate Advancement.  But they didn't, so imho, the game suffers.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Another drawback to WoW is the playerbase.  It is a much younger audience in WoW than we ever had in EQ.  WoW is full of the gotta have it now kids with the E-Peen disease.  Where you can find a lot of help in OOC chat in EQ, you get mostly insults in WoW.  It's just the nature of the playerbase.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;All things considered, WoW is a great game until you hit the level cap - from that point on its a boring grindfest.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;EQ2 has a rich, highly detailed world that feels like it has no soul.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;EQ1 is the only one that has the variety, longevity and playerbase that keeps me coming back.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;I can't speak for many of the other MMO's out there....I played DAoC for about a week when it first came out and was not impressed enough to leave EQ, beyond that, maybe some others can offer some info on them.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;</description>
